I /don&#39;t/ recommend the book &quot;C++ Neural Networks and Fuzzy Logic&quot; by Rao 
and Rao (although it sounds like it would fit your experience). I used it 
for some NN work I did in highschool and I honestly don&#39;t think it clearly 
explains anything.

I&#39;m not sure what your plans are, but taking an NN class may be the best 
way to get the experience you want. A good professor can usually answer 
your questions and point you in the right direction on research themes. 
The most important thing about NNs is understanding the concepts, and the 
differences between network models (e.g. when would you use 
cascade-correlation, when would you use a SOM?), because once you have 
that, the coding is generally very straightforward.

-- Joe

